The explicit purpose of this category is to identify those redirects that, at some future point, could be expanded into new, dedicated articles, templates, or other project pages. This typically occurs when the target page grows unwieldy, or when a topic's complexity demands its own space for comprehensive treatment. When the time is right, or when an editor decides the time is right, this redirect may be replaced with content "carved out" from the target page, providing a more focused and detailed exposition. It’s a continuous process of refinement and specialization, much like the universe itself, endlessly expanding and differentiating. For further guidance on how to manage these nuanced relationships, one might consult `{{[R to section](/Template:R_to_section)}}`, which is often used in conjunction with this redirect category when the redirect points to a specific segment of a larger article.

##### Avoiding Over-Optimization: Direct Links and Double Redirects

It is crucial to understand that, precisely because a new page *may* eventually be created at this location, links pointing to this redirect should **not** be indiscriminately replaced with direct links to the current target page. Doing so would necessitate a tedious update of all those links if and when the redirect is converted into an article, thus defeating the purpose of the redirect as a flexible navigational aid. To manage the creation of redirects that point *to* this page, the `{{[R avoided double redirect](/Template:R_avoided_double_redirect)}}` template is utilized. This prevents the creation of a "double redirect," which occurs when a redirect points to another redirect, an inefficient and generally frowned-upon practice in the intricate world of wiki-navigation. It's a bureaucratic hurdle designed to prevent digital dead ends, a small mercy in a world full of them.

